I know that there have been attempts
to make us feel integrated, and I appreci-
ate that. There are evening activities every
Wednesday hosted by the Commuter Stu-
dent Association on campus along with
other events for ﬁrst-year commuters. I
also recall attending several of the twice-
monthly “Soup and Substance” sessions,

which included a department guest speaker, .

and well, soup. The attempts to integrate
us were made, and they were appreciated.

Commuters swiftly travel through the
climate changes of Pittsburgh with sturdy

boots and heavy backpacks. While we don’t
receive the luxury of roaming the campus
in pajama pants when we please, we can
make the most of our time as commuters
at Pitt. And there are other options for ac-
tivities available to us, despite our difficult
schedules.

Commuter students have options to
make connections, even if it might be more
difficult for them than for peers who live on

_ campus. The Commuter Student Lounge is

actually a suitable “home away from home.”
I remember sharing countless hours there
laughing at “fail” videos between classes.
