Politics and sports have officially collided,
and football is drowning because of it.

There is no way around it anymore: My
least favorite institution has found its way
into my favorite institution, and now I must
suffer.

Don’t get me wrong, I’m all for a good
political discussion, a heated debate on gun
control or religion in school. But in modern
America, the political realm seems to stand
more on money and corruption than it does
on merit and people. "

Now I know what you’re thinking — what,
sports isn’t about money? Referees are never
corrupt? I’d never make such a claim, at least
not these days. -

But just consider President Barack Obama
dipping his toes into the sports world when
he made his comments last week about fear-
ing for his child’s safety if he were to play
football. ‘

My immediate reaction was sour. What
does it say when our president takes a stand
against something like football‘? How did
we go from heroism to player safety on our
holy gridiron?

While I believe in the sincerity of Obama’s
comments and his concern about the safety
aspect of football, I believe he (and we) have
lost sight of all the incredible things football
has done for our country and more impor-
tantly, our people.

No more are the days when we think of
football and talk about how many children’s
lives it has saved.

No more are the days when we think of
football and talk about how many kids from
inner-city schools could have spent the hours
between dismissal and their mom coming
home on drugs after engaging in gang-related
activities.

No more are the days when we think of
football and then think of the success sto-
ries of athletes who came from nothing and
earned college degrees to ultimately con-
tribute to our nation’s economy. This is a
contribution that would have been impos-
sible without an outlet for their natural gifts.

No more are the days when we think of
football and talk about that feeling of stand-_
ing shoulder to shoulder with your brothers,

